Logical Operators

When we need to test for 2 or more conditions we use Logical Operators

    AND OR NOT
    &&  ||  !


boolean cold=true;
boolean rain=true;


AND

true && true -> TRUE
true && false -> FALSE
false && true -> FALSE
false && false -> FALSE


OR

true || true -> TRUE
true || false -> TRUE
false || true -> TRUE
false || false -> FALSE



if (cold, rain) {
        sout ("I will stay at home");
}


NOT - reverse the condition

       boolean boo=!false;
       sout(boo); // true


Switch Statement -

syntax

switch (variable) {

case value1:
        code A;
        break;
case value2:
        code B;
        break;
default:
        Code C;
        break;
}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Loop - repeat block of code based on the condition


4 loops in JAVA:
while
do while
for
for each/advanced for loop/enhanced for loop

/*
So a for loop is more useful when you know in advance the number of iterations you want to do,
and while is good for cases where the number of iteration is unknown but it depends on some condition.
/*